2026-03-16 10:11:54,931 - OrderManager - INFO - Generated 4 signals: [{'contract_month': '202605', 'prediction_type': 'DIRECTIONAL', 'direction': 'BEARISH', 'reason': 'The Permabear case is more grounded in the current packet because it stacks multiple independent, directly-relevant lines of evidence that all point the same way: (1) supply forecasts have moved to “record” territory from multiple forecasters (Conab; StoneX; Rabobank), and StoneX’s revision is explicitly described as a significant upward revision; (2) ICE-certified stocks are rising in a sustained, rapid build per the Inventory Report; (3) spot futures are already easing toward $2.80/lb with attribution to record production forecasts and favorable Minas Gerais weather; and (4) macro/FX adds a mild additional headwind via a weaker BRL over the past month (Macro Report’s own revised conclusion tilts mildly bearish). These are fundamental/flow signals, not just chart interpretation.\n\nThe Permabull does identify real bullish risks—logistics friction (Santos congestion, freight increases, Red Sea/Hormuz delays) and agronomic quality risk from extreme rainfall and disease potential—and those are supported by the Geopolitical, Supply Chain, and Agronomist reports. However, the bull’s conclusion that these factors “preserve near-term tightness” is weaker than the bear’s surplus thesis because the current data also shows inventories building (ICE certified stocks) while prices drift lower, suggesting the market is presently weighting future supply and the availability of deliverable coffee more than it is weighting transit delays. The bull also leans on some weaker/indirect evidence (soy farmer selling as a proxy for coffee; “contrarian” inference from put skew) that the Macro and Volatility reports themselves caution against over-interpreting.\n\nOn the “priced-in” check, logistics shocks did create a prior spike (+9.55 c/lb on March 5), but price has since softened, which supports the bear’s argument that 